  "Notice that even though our \u0000SKIP#164\u0000 component is a few layers deep and doesn't receive any props, we can still access the \u0000SKIP#165\u0000 object via \u0000SKIP#166\u0000.": "",
  "In a way, you can kind of think of using Context as creating \"shadow props\" –&nbsp;where you're making data available to a component, just without having to explicitly pass it down.": "",
  "Now admittedly there is one thing strange about this demo you may have noticed. Since \u0000SKIP#167\u0000 is just a static object, why don't we just \u0000SKIP#168\u0000 it from a module and \u0000SKIP#169\u0000 it wherever we need it? There's not really a need for Context in this scenario.": "",
  "The reason I chose this example is because it demonstrate how Context works without having to worry about \"managing\" state, and in fact, as we saw –&nbsp;it has nothing to do with state at all. Context is purely just a mechanism for teleporting data.": "",
  "This is a huge misconception when it comes to Context. Whether what you're teleporting is a static object, function, state, or anything else –&nbsp;it doesn't change that fact that Context is a teleporter, not a manager of state.": "",
  "This also makes Context a little difficult to teach. It's not that Context itself is difficult, as you saw. It's that Context is most appropriately used in large applications with deeply nested component architectures where passing props becomes unreasonable. So, by definition, it's hard to create a small demo app that represents that use case.": "",
